^*BBridge Base Inc.^*N President ^*BFred Gitelman^*N (the author of ^*BThe Deal of the Week^*N) was part of the Canadian Team for this event. The next several ^*BDeals of the Week^*N will be an account of Fred's experiences in Salt Lake City. These accounts will be written in the first person and, unlike most ^*BDeals of the Week^*N, will focus on deals that were critical in this event (as opposed to deals that are technically complex).

The IOC Grand Prix has traditionally been held at the Olympic Museum in Lausanne, Switzerland. The World Bridge Federation hopes that this event (especially the 2002 edition which coincided with the Winter Olympics) will help convince the International Olympic Committee to accept bridge as an Olympic sport. Regardless of whether or not they are successful in this regard, the WBF should be commended for running a fine event and attracting a great deal of media attention at the 2002 IOC Grand Prix.

10 mens teams, 10 womens teams, and 4 junior teams were invited to Salt Lake City. My partner ^*BJoey Silver^*N and I played for Canada in this event. The rest of our team consisted of ^*BNick Gartaganis^*N (our Captain) playing with ^*BPeter Jones^*N, and ^*BGord Campbell^*N playing with ^*BKeith Balcombe^*N. The event consisted of a complete round robin of 12 board matches with 4 teams qualifying for a 48-board semi-final followed by a 48-board final.

|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


nt|
The word on the street was that Canada was unlikely to make the final 4 as it was expected that 6 very strong teams (Brazil, Indonesia, Italy, Norway, Poland, and the United States) would battle it out for the top 4 spots. The other 4 teams (Australia, Canada, Egypt, and India) were not expected to be a factor in this event.

While I did not exactly think we were a favorite to qualify in the top 4, I knew we had a chance. I knew from experience that it was possible for a team like ours to defeat the best teams in the world. Also, I had a lot of confidence in my partnership with Joey and, while my teammates were almost totally lacking in international experience, they had a few things going for them:

1) They have been the most consistent team in the Canadian National Teams Championships over the last 5 years or so. They always seem to advance well into the knockout phase of this event and they won the 2001 CNTC (thereby earning the right to play in Salt Lake City). Having lost convincingly to the Gartaganis team in the 1998 CNTC, I knew that these guys could play.

2) I knew that everyone on the team would be good partners and teammates through thick and thin. This is important as there are bound to be both thick and thin moments in a bridge touranment like the IOC Grand Prix. Receiving support from your partner and teammates during thin times is conducive to winning bridge tournaments.

3) I knew that our captain, Nick Gartaganis, had all of the necessary qualities to do his job well. Nick is well-organized, good with people, and good at strategy. Furthermore, he had the respect of the rest of the team and was quite capable of separating his ego as a bridge player from the lineup decisions that he was going to have to make.

